			<ul class="comment b2" id="comment-916611">
				
				<li class="comment-author" >
                    
                        <div class="badges">
                            
                                



                            
                        </div>
                        <div class="profile" >
                            
                                

<img class="author-profile-picture" src="http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/site_furniture/2010/09/01/no-user-image.gif" height="60" width="60" alt="" />
<a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/discussion/user/asyn" title="User profile page">asyn</a>

                            
                            <p class="date">18 February 2008 5:10AM</p>
                        </div>
                    
					<div class="comment-body">
						
							<p>The article makes a valid if somewhat laboured (did it have to be that long?) point about civil liberties,it missed or deliberately ignored the opportunity to point out that issuing this kind of permit would be a welcome contribution to reducing the worrying trend of increased smoking in the underage group. Balance, Charlie, balance.</p><p>As for the comments above, perhaps raging at "sanctimonious non-smokers", as annoying as they may be, is a way for smokers to pump themselves up with indignation and ignore the fact that smoking in isolation from other people only damages one's own health whereas social smoking (the most common form) demonstrably damages others'. Comments putting smoke on a par with obnoxious perfume (which is proven not to harm lungs, as umpleasant as it may be), etc, merely demonstrate ignorance or pigheadedness in the face of facts.</p><p>On another note many companies in Japan do enforce collective exercise for their employees, and the Japanese have the longest life expectancy in the world. Japan also has one of the highest proportions of smokers in the developed world, however. Or maybe smokers could choose to undertake a form of payment by exercise rather than a financial one for the privilege of smoking, thus alleviating the burden their habit places on public health organisations.</p>
						
					</div>
				</li>
				
